                <h3>Driving While Suspended</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                When charged with DWLS in Florida, you are exposed to two different violations. oneThere are two types of 
                DWLS, with knowledge and without knowledge. If you are charged with DWLS having received a notice about your
                 license suspension, it is considered a criminal traffic violation. If you are charged with DWLS without 
                knowledge it is a civil traffic violation. Since Driving on a Suspended License with knowledge is a criminal 
                infraction, you are REQUIRED to appear in court. Florida Statute 322.34 (2) provides, a person commits a 
                misdemeanor of the second degree when they are convicted of driving while license suspended on the first 
                offense. Your driving record will still be affected with a DWLS charge even if adjudication is withheld. 
                The DHSMV will still count the offense as a major moving violation for purposes of Habitulalization.
            </p>
            <p>
                Driving While License Suspended without knowing is a civil infraction. Florida statute 322.34 (1) states 
                that someone driving their vehicle without knowing that their license is suspended is guilty of a moving
                 violation. Aside from being adjudicated guilty and having three points assessed on your license, a DWLS 
                without knowledge citation can considerably affect the status of your license if you have at least two other 
                major violations on your driving record.
            </p>
            <p>
                It may be the case for you that the notice of your suspension never reached you home. Most of our clients never
                 received it from the Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles. Usually this happens because the 
                letter was sent to the last known address on file and there is no confirmation that you received the letter.
            </p>
        </div>



        <!-- ------------------------------------Driving Under the Influence------------------------------------------- -->
        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile" aria-labelledby="profile-tab">
            <div class="pensyl">
                <h3>Driving Under the Influence</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                If you are charged with Driving Under the Influence you have to be prepared in how to enhance your defense.
                 Many people charged with this crime have never been involved in the court system and are unfamiliar with the
                 long lasting effects of a DUI conviction. Therefore, speak with a lawyer from our team immediately as soon 
                as possible in order to ensure that each variable is scrutinized and defended carefully. Just one flaw can 
                make a huge difference in the outcome of your case. Our duty is to evaluate the facts of your particular case
                 and determine the very best defense strategy for your case. The moment we find the Achilles' heel of the 
                states' case, we will use our skills to win.
            </p>
            <p><b>Under Florida Law, a person is guilty of the offense of Driving Under the Influence if the person is:</b></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Under the influence of any alcoholic beverage or chemical substances when affected to the extent their normal
                     faculties are impaired</li>
                <li>The person has a breath alcohol content over .08. “Chemical substances” may include illegal substances such as 
                    marijuana, prescription medication or cocaine. Evidence of impairment of a person’s normal faculties include a 
                    slower reaction time, speeding, weaving, driving too slow, slurred speech, glassy eyes and difficulty with balance.
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Sentence guidelines for DUI charges are not high in The State of Florida. Possible sanctions include: jail time 
                (depending on the facts), driver’s license suspension, community service, DUI school, victim impact panel, 
                fines, community service, vehicle impound and installation of an ignition interlock device in your vehicle.
                 We will work tirelessly on your behalf to minimize these sanctions and get your case reduced to a lesser 
                charge so some.
            </p>
            <p>
                A common result of your DUI charge is your licenses being suspended by the DHSMV. This happens if you refused to
                 provide a breath, urine, or blood sample or if you provided a breath sample with a result of a .08 or higher. 
                Our attorneys will not only fight your criminal charge but also fight your license suspension by the Department 
                of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles. Remember that only 10 days are given to you after your arrest to have the 
                hearing set to fight your suspension.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- ------------------------------------ Refusal to Submit to a Breath Test------------------------------------------ -->


        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile3" aria-labelledby="profile-tab2">
            <div class="pensyl">
                <h3>Refusal to Submit to a Breath Test</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                Failing to Submit to a Breath Test means that a person has refused to take a chemical test of his or her 
                breath, blood, or urine and that his or her driving privilege was previously suspended for a prior refusal 
                to submit to a lawful test of his or her breath, urine, or blood. This charge, known as Florida Statute 
                316.1939, is often used by the State Attorney’s office as leverage in a pending DUI case. It is less complex
                 for the prosecution to provide evidence because under Florida law the DHSMV’s records showing that a person’s
                 license has been previously suspended for a prior refusal to submit to a lawful test of his or her breath, 
                urine, or blood shall be admissible and shall create a rebuttable presumption of the previous suspension.
            </p>
            <p>
                When you are charged with this offense, you may be face up to a year in the county jail, and/or 12 months of 
                probation, and a possible fine of up to $1000, plus court costs and prosecutor fees assessed by the Court.
            </p>
            <div class="Footertext">
                <h5>
                    <center>If you were charged with this offense, contact our office immediately and have one of our attorneys represent you.</center>
                </h5>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ------------------------------------ Reckless Driving------------------------------------------ -->


        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile4" aria-labelledby="profile-tab3">
            <div class="pensyl">
                <h3>Reckless Driving</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                If you are charge with a Reckless Driving ticket, it basically means that you were driving in an unsafe manner, posing a danger to people 
                or property. If you are convicted of this crime, 4 points will be assessed to your driving record. A person 
                charged for the first time The Florida Statute 316.192 could face up to 60 days in the county jail and/or a 
                fine up to $500 upon conviction. If this is a second or subsequent offense a person could be facing up to 6 
                months in the county jail and/or a fine up to $1000. If the reckless driving offense involved damage to any 
                person or property, the penalties may be enhanced. For example, a serious bodily injury to another as a result
                 of the reckless driving the person could be charged with a third degree felony. A third degree felony is
                 punishable by up to 5 years in Florida State Prison. Furthermore, if the court has reasonable cause to 
                believe that alcohol, chemical substances, or controlled substances are a factor a person may be facing 
                additional sanctions. Under the law, and based up the facts and your criminal history, the prosecutor can 
                exercise discretion and offer a withhold of adjudication. That means that you will not be formally convicted 
                of the offense and the DHSMV will not put points on your license.
            </p>
            <p>
                In some cases, DUI offenses are reduced to a reckless driving, a reduced charge in the State of Florida. 
                Florida statute 316.192(5) allows the Court to accept a plea and sentence someone to a penalty if the Court 
                determines that alcohol was a significant factor then the Court will order the driver to complete a DUI
                 school and can place the motorist on probation for up to 12 months.
            </p>
            <div class="Footertext">
                <h5>
                    <center>Contact our office at 877-VIOLATION and prevent a potential criminal history on your driving record.</center>
                </h5>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ------------------------------------  Habitual Traffic Offender------------------------------------------ -->



        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile5" aria-labelledby="profile-tab4">
