                <h3>Habitual Traffic Offender</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                There are two types of a Habitual Traffic Offender (HTO) charge: a first degree misdemeanor or a third degree 
                felony under Florida law. When charged with a first degree misdemeanor the person may face up to 11 months 
                and 29 days in the county jail. A third degre felony is punishable by up to 5 years in Florida State Prison. 
                The State Attorney is able to prosecute this charge even if the driver was not aware that he/she was 
                classified as a Habitual Traffic Offender. Therefore, even if a driver paid all their remaining citations 
                they can still be prosecuted. If you are a Habitual Traffic Offender, do not wait and contact our team 
                immediately to evaluate your driving record and provide with the best results for this charge. We do 
                everything possible to get your license back as well as working out the charge with the State Attorney.
            </p>
        </div>


        <!-- ------------------------------------ Leaving the Scene of an Accident------------------------------------------ -->


        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile6" aria-labelledby="profile-tab5">
            <div class="pensyl">
                <h3>Leaving the Scene of an Accident</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                Leaving the Scene of an Accident charges are separated into two categories. The first category is a second
                 degree misdemeanor offense that is punishable by up to 60 days in the county jail, $500 fine, and/or 6
                 months of probation. Depending on the severity of the accident you could be charged with a misdemeanor or
                 felony leaving the scene. Florida Statute 316.061 states that the driver of any vehicle involved in a crash
                 resulting only in damage to a vehicle or other property which is driven or attended by any person shall
                 immediately stop such vehicle at the scene of such crash or as close as possible, and shall forthwith return
                 to, and in every event shall reamin at, the scene of the crash until he or she has fulfilled the requirements
                 of Florida Statute 316.062.
            </p>
            <p>
                If you are facing this charge, It is imperative that you contact our office immediately at 877-VIOLATION. There usually is
                 evidence, such as 911 calls, that is only available for a limited amount of time. In addition to the criminal sanctions,
                 if you get convicted for leaving the scene of an accident the DHSMV will assess 6 points on your driving record. However,
                 based on the facts of the case and your criminal history the Prosecutor may exercise discretion and offer a withhold of 
                adjudication, meaning that you are not formally convicted of the offense and will not have points assessed on your driving
                 record.
            </p>
        </div>


        <!-- ------------------------------------ Violation of Business Purposes------------------------------------------ -->


        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile7" aria-labelledby="profile-tab6">
            <div class="pensyl">
                <h3>Violation of Business Purposes</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                After your license has been suspended or revoked, it may be possible to obtain a hardship license. 
                Depending on the type of hardship license, your driving will be restricted in scope. After you attend a 
                hearing at the DHSMV and a restriction is placed on your license, it is important you apply these
                 restrictions when driving, otherwise, you can be charged with a criminal violation. You may be arrested
                 and forced to spend the night in jail. Some of the restrictions may include business purposes only, 
                employment only, ignition interlock, or eyeglasses. If you are on probation, that will subject you to a
                 violation of probation warrant being signed for your arrest. Aside from any penalty that the court will 
                impose on your criminal case, if you get convicted of violating your restricted license you will lose your
                 restriction.
            </p>
            <p>
                In some cases, a business purposes only license is given as a result of a habitual traffic offender revocation. 
                When you get convicted, you lose your restriction and are forced to wait one year before you can reapply. In Florida, 
                not having a license is a brutal consequence of not paying off tickets in time or accumulating a habitual revocation. 
                HOWEVER, if the Court and the state attorney is willing to withhold adjudication, then your restriction will not be lost
                 and you will be able to cotinue to drive.
            </p>
            <p>
                Contact our office immediately to speak with one of our attorneys and determine if there are legal defenses to the charge. 
                Depending on what your driver’s license restriction is, the State Attorney’s Office will often seek substantial jail time.
                 We are committed to achieve the best outcome for you.
            </p>
        </div>


