        <!-- ------------------------------------  Unlawful Display of a License------------------------------------------ -->


        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile15" aria-labelledby="profile-tab14">
            <div class="pensyl">
                <h3>Unlawful Display of a License</h3>
            </div>

            <p><b>It is unlawful to perform any of following actions with a driver's license:</b></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Display or represent any driver’s license not issued to you.</li>
                <li>Display a driver’s license that has been canceled, revoked, suspended, or disqualified.</li>
                <li>Allow someone else to unlawfully use a license issued to you</li>
                <li>Have in your possession two driver’s licenses.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                All of these offenses are criminal infractions punishable up to 60 days in the county jail, a fine of up to 
                $500, and/or up to 6 months of probation. We have represented numerous individuals over the years who 
                changed their address with the DMV, received a new license but didn’t destroy their old one. Keep in mind 
                that the law allows you to only possess one valid Florida license at a time.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- ------------------------------------ Permitting Unauthorized Person to Drive------------------------------------------ -->


        <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane fade" id="profile16" aria-labelledby="profile-tab15">
            <div class="pensyl">
                <h3>Permitting Unauthorized Person to Drive</h3>
            </div>

            <p>
                <b>This charge is broken into two types of offenses: allowing an unauthorized minor to drive or permitting an 
                unauthorized operator to drive.</b>
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Florida Statute 322.35 provides, no person shall cause or knowingly permit his or her child or ward under 
                    the age of 18 years to drive a motor vehicle upon any highway when such minor is not authorized.</li>
                <li>Florida Statute 322.36 provides, a person may not authorize or knowingly permit a motor vehicle owned by
                     him or her or under his or her dominion or control to be operated upon any highway or public street 
                    except by a person who is duly authorized to operate a motor vehicle under this chapter. For example, 
                    if you allow a friend to operate your vehicle knowing that his/her license is suspended.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Both of these charges are criminal traffic violations charged as a second-degree misdemeanor. If an accident is 
                involved, then the Court may suspend your license for 1 year in addition and you could be facing jail for up to 
                60 days, fines of up to $500 and court costs, and probation for up to 6 months.
            </p>
